<HL>
   Mideast Crisis Dashes Hopes for Rebound
   In Corporate Profits in the Second Half
   ----
   By Ralph E. Winter
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The likelihood of a second-half rebound in corporate
profits all but died with Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
   Many U.S. manufacturers had expected 1990 profits to be
the mirror image of 1989 results, starting out slowly as
companies completed the inventory reduction begun in late
1989, but then improving noticeably in the second half. The
oil crisis makes it more likely that profits will continue to
slip until sometime in 1991.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Even optimistic economists who don't expect higher oil
prices to trigger a recession say after-tax corporate profits
will decline in 1990 for the second consecutive year. Richard
D. Rippe, senior vice president and chief economist with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., is looking for a 2% to 3% dip from
1989's $167.1 billion.
   Among the more bearish forecasters, A. Gary Shilling, New
York economic consultant, says the crisis is "the last nail
in the coffin of this expansion." He's forecasting a 12% to
14% profit drop for 1990. David Bostian, managing director
and chief economist for Jesup, Josephthal &amp; Co., believes "we
were in a recession before the invasion occurred." Piling on
the Middle East crisis will produce some "downright scary"
earnings reports because of "the downside leverage of high
corporate debt."
   Even before Saddam Hussein plunged across the border, the
profit outlook was less favorable than manufacturing
executives had expected during the spring. Demand was a
little weaker than anticipated, triggering discounting on
products ranging from tires to machine tools and preventing
producers of other items from raising prices to pass through
higher costs. And costs rose a little more than had been
budgeted.
   In addition, many multinational corporations are incurring
losses in Brazil. The combination drove profits in the second
quarter down 11% from a year earlier, according to a Wall
Street Journal compilation of reports from 639 major
companies.
   The Mideast crisis compounds those problems. Even if oil
prices level off in the low to mid $20s for the rest of this
year, the bill for oil and basic chemical feedstocks will
rise 25% or more at many factories. It will be hard to pass
that along, particularly if uncertainty created by the
invasion causes both consumers and companies to rein in their
spending a bit.
   Dow Chemical Co. provides a good illustration of the
profit problems. The Midland, Mich., chemicals and plastics
producer reported a 50% drop in second-quarter net, shocking
industry analysts who looked for a more moderate drop from
last year's unusually fat profits. Dow officials said
second-half earnings would be even weaker than the first
half. Anticipated price increases hadn't appeared, and prices
of some products, such as polyethylene, actually declined,
Dow says. Also, the construction, automotive and furniture
markets are weaker than expected.
   Rising oil prices worsen the outlook, Dow says, but it's
too early to estimate how seriously. Dow's plants use huge
amounts of energy, and oil is a basic feedstock for many of
its plastics and organic chemicals. The extent of the profit
drop will depend on Dow's success in passing through those
cost increases.
   Furthermore, there are few pluses for business in the
current crisis, other than for oil producers and oil-field
service concerns. And the oil companies already are under
political pressure to hold down prices; there's talk of
additional taxes to siphon off any windfall profits.
   The first impact of the crisis will be weaker sales
arising from increased uncertainty. Companies insist that
they're proceeding with capital spending programs, product
development and other long-term projects. Most will do that.
Some plant managers may place orders quickly, before the
authority to do so is revoked by skittish boards. But more
companies will move a little more slowly as they watch
Mideast developments.
   More important, they're likely to hold back on routine
replacements of trucks, machinery and office equipment, says
Stephen R. Hardis, vice chairman and chief financial and
administrative officer of Eaton Corp., Cleveland-based maker
of truck parts and electrical and electronic products.
Already companies such as American Steel &amp; Wire Corp.,
Cuyahoga Heights, Ohio, say they're watching inventories and
expenses a little more closely.
   Consumers, who already were dragging their feet on
purchases of cars, appliances and other major items, also are
likely to pause, at least briefly. Besides, a little more of
their money is going abroad as they pay higher prices for
gasoline and heating oil.
   And if the crisis drags on until Christmas, the year's
biggest shopping season could suffer. "And there are a lot of
shaky retailers out there," adds Gary E. Morin, vice
president for finance and chief financial officer of Huffy
Corp., the nation's largest bicycle maker. "If they don't
have a good Christmas, manufacturers will be writing off a
lot of receivables" as the retailers fold.
   As Mr. Bostian suggests, the profit impact of the weaker
sales will be amplified by high corporate interest expense
and other fixed costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900813-0125
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900813-0125.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Deloitte &amp; Touche Declines to Continue
   As Auditor of Troubled First Executive
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   FEXC
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
ACCOUNTING (ACC)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- First Executive Corp., the wounded
insurance holding company, said its longtime auditor,
Deloitte &amp; Touche, has declined to continue in that capacity.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
the company said it hasn't had any disagreements with
Deloitte &amp; Touche in the past 2 1/2 years, and the reason for
the firm's decision to remove itself remains unclear.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First Executive, the parent of Executive Life Insurance
Co., a California concern, and Executive Life Insurance Co.
of New York, has been the subject of widespread news coverage
since earlier this year, when it reported an $859 million
write-down of its junk-bond portfolio. The unexpected
write-down, which applied as of Dec. 31, 1989, brought the
company's net loss for last year to $775.6 million, or $9.67
a share.
   First Executive noted in its filing that, in June, it
hired William L. Sanders as chief financial officer,
treasurer and a corporate vice president. Mr. Sanders had
been the Deloitte &amp; Touche partner in charge of First
Executive's audit since 1986.
   Subsequent to hiring Mr. Sanders, First Executive said, it
recruited a number of other Deloitte &amp; Touche employees who
also had worked on its audit. First Executive said it
employed the former members of the group that audited it "in
order to expand its accounting staff."
   The company said that, because of the resulting changes at
Deloitte &amp; Touche, it had begun considering a possible change
of accountants but hadn't reached any decision when Deloitte
&amp; Touche apparently beat it to the punch and resigned.
However, the filing doesn't explicitly connect Deloitte &amp;
Touche's decision to resign with First Executive's unusual
decision to employ what appears to have been a substantial
portion of its outside auditor's team.
   First Executive's disclosure was made in an 8-K
extraordinary events filing with the SEC. The filing, dated
July 30, was signed by a corporate officer Aug. 2 and
received by the commission the next day.
   For its part, Deloitte &amp; Touche, in an attached
one-sentence letter, said it concurred with First Executive's
"comments" in the 8-K filing but didn't provide further
disclosure. Robert Garland, managing partner of Deloitte &amp;
Touche's Los Angeles office, declined to elaborate.
   Fred Carr, chairman and chief executive officer of First
Executive, said the company hasn't selected a successor to
Deloitte &amp; Touche. Before a merger that created Deloitte &amp;
Touche, a predecessor firm, Touche Ross &amp; Co., had audited
First Executive. "They are an excellent firm, and we have
enjoyed an excellent relationship with them," Mr. Carr said,
adding that he had discussed Deloitte &amp; Touche's decision to
withdraw as auditor at First Executive's July 30 annual
meeting.
   Mr. Carr said he wasn't sure how many members of Deloitte
&amp; Touche's former audit team had been recruited by First
Executive. "I'm guessing that it's seven or eight," he said.
   Deloitte &amp; Touche is a defendant with First Executive in
shareholder suits focusing, among other things, on alleged
inadequate disclosure of the company's troubled financial
condition.
   Over the years, the accounting firm has issued a series of
unqualified audit opinions on First Executive. However, in
its March 29, 1990 report on the 1989 financial statements,
Deloitte &amp; Touche included extensive cautionary explanations.
Among other things, it said that the estimated market value
of First Executive's $8 billion-plus junk-bond holdings was
based on the company's and certain brokers' subjective
determinations because the market for some of the securities
was either too volatile or too illiquid to get a clear
reading.
   However, the auditor's letter didn't flag or explain the
$859 million write-down or note that, even after the
write-down, the company's market value of the bond portfolio
remained about $1 billion below the $13.26 billion value at
which it is recorded on First Executive's books. Deloitte &amp;
Touche did note, however, that if troubled market conditions
continue, the company could suffer greater portfolio losses
than then estimated.
   First Executive is the subject of a number of regulatory
inquiries, among them a formal SEC investigation begun in
March that is looking into the company's financial
statements, including the bond-portfolio write-down.
   As its financial woes deepened this year, including more
than $1.33 billion paid in the first quarter to holders
cashing in policies, First Executive began pointing to
studies by consulting actuaries Milliman &amp; Robertson, which
it said proved that its California-based Executive Life
Insurance unit was financially sound and able to withstand a
variety of hypothetical adversities.
   But, while reporting the good news, First Executive thus
far has refused to make the reports themselves public.
   Friday, New York's state appeals court delayed ruling on
an appeal by First Executive to forestall disclosure of the
reports to Joseph Belth, publisher of "Insurance Forum," and
a frequent critic of First Executive. A lower court had
ordered the New York State Department of Insurance, which has
copies of the reports, to make them public under state
freedom of information statutes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900813-0124
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900813-0124.
