<LP>
   IRAQ SAID it would withdraw from Kuwait if Israel pulls
out of the West Bank.
   The "initiative" offered by Iraq's Hussein, which was
designed to rally Arabs, also demanded a Syrian pullback from
Lebanon. The U.S. and Israel rejected the conditions. Baker,
noting that Kuwait's ousted government asked the U.S. to
enforce a U.N. trade embargo, said "interdiction" of Iraqi
shipments would get under way immediately. Three thousand
Egyptian soldiers arrived in Saudi Arabia, the vanguard of a
10,000-member Arab force including Syria and Morocco.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Britain said one of its citizens was shot Saturday by an
Iraqi soldier in Kuwait, while Baghdad gave conflicting
reports on the status of foreigners in Iraq and Kuwait. In
Saudi Arabia, an American airman died in an accident.
   ---
   Washington's Barry urged federal prosecutors over the
weekend not to retry him on drug and perjury charges. On
Friday, a jury convicted the mayor on one misdemeanor
cocaine-possession charge, acquitted him of another
misdemeanor and deadlocked on 12 counts. Barry has said he
won't seek re-election for mayor.
   ---
   A former Thornburgh aide was indicted Friday on
cocaine-related charges. The indictment was returned by a
grand jury in Harrisburg, Pa., against Henry Barr, who quit
his Justice Department post in May 1989. Barr had coordinated
criminal investigations for Thornburgh, including those
involving drugs.
   ---
   The FDA approved new clinical trials for a drug that some
say can prolong the lives of AIDS patients and people
infected with the AIDS virus, officials said Saturday. An FDA
spokesman said a double-blind study will begin next month
using the anti-viral compound Ampligen, with about 135
patients in as many as eight cities participating.
   ---
   At least 20,000 gallons of oil spilled into the Houston
Ship Channel as a barge buckled, just two days after the
Coast Guard completed a two-week cleanup of a 700,000-gallon
spill resulting from a tanker-barge collision. The ship
channel remained open, but Texas officials warned ships to
slow down because of the new spill.
   ---
   Lightning fires burned more than 200,000 acres of
California forest in the past week, and fire officials said
the situation could get get "much, much worse" because of a
lengthy drought. In Yosemite National Park, off limits to
tourists since Friday, two fires burned more than 15,000
acres.
   ---
   A federal judge in Los Angeles ruled Friday that a Mexican
doctor accused in the torture-slaying of U.S. undercover drug
agent Camarena must be returned home because federal agents
illegally ordered the doctor's kidnapping. Dr. Humberto
Alvarez Machain's abduction soured diplomatic relations
between the U.S. and Mexico.
   ---
   Colombian police killed a key member of the Medellin
cocaine cartel Saturday in a gun battle in one of Medellin's
exclusive neighborhoods. Police officials said the dead man,
Gustavo de Jesus Gaviria, was responsible for coordinating
terrorist bombings and assassinations in Colombia and
shipments of cocaine to the U.S. and Europe.
   ---
   Pakistan's new government began rounding up supporters of
ousted Prime Minister Bhutto as a cabinet minister
acknowledged that the caretaker rulers faced a crisis of
confidence. Bhutto was fired last week by President Ishaq
Khan, who accused her of corruption and abuse of power.
   ---
   Zaire's President Mobutu rules his country by violently
suppressing the opposition, despite his promises of political
reform, the New York-based Lawyers Committee for Human Rights
charged. The committee said Mobutu's security forces have
maintained control through a policy of political killings,
torture, arbitrary arrests and harassment.
   ---
   Suspected Tamil rebels killed at least 144 Moslems in six
villages in eastern Sri Lanka over the weekend, according to
military sources and Moslem leaders. In retaliation, Moslems
reportedly attacked a Tamil refugee camp and slaughtered 37
Tamils.
   ---
   Liberia's President Doe plans to stay in office for at
least a year after a West African peacekeeping force
intervenes in the nation's civil war, an official said. The
five-nation group is due to arrive within days.
   ---
   Wayne Grady won the PGA Championship golf title at Shoal
Creek Country Club, Birmingham, Ala., by three strokes.
