<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Radio for A New Europe
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   For decades Albania was viewed as a hermit country, its
people completely cut off from news of the West and content
with Communist poverty. The recent exodus of 5,000 refugees
to the West has shattered that myth. It turns out Albanians
are well informed about freedom, in large part from listening
to U.S.-sponsored broadcasts such as the Voice of America.
   Amazingly, many of the refugees speak English, which they
had painstakingly taught themselves by listening to the VOA.
The knowledge that the Iron Curtain had fallen gave them the
courage to try fleeing from the last Stalinist regime in
Europe.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For 40 years, the VOA along with Radio Free Europe and
Radio Liberty (which broadcasts to the Soviet Union) have
beamed objective news into nations lacking a free press. They
played a significant role in the collapse of communism in
Eastern Europe. Lech Walesa has said that without Radio Free
Europe's Polish broadcasts, Solidarity would have ceased to
exist.
   Now that communism is becoming a spent historical force,
many in Congress are calling for a swift end to U.S. funding
of Radio Free Europe and a curtailment of VOA's budget. They
fail to recognize that having helped win the Cold War, U.S.
radio stations are greatly needed to secure the peace in
Eastern Europe. In addition, people in oppressed regions of
Asia and Africa still desperately need the news and culture
they provide.
   Radio Free Europe can still perform a vital role in the
nations of Eastern Europe, which may have freedom of speech
but still lack broadbased broadcasting outlets independent of
the state. RFE's programming, for instance, now includes
tutorials on building democratic institutions, the role of a
free press and creating free markets.
   The new democratic leaders of Eastern Europe welcome RFE's
continued competition. In May, Czechoslovakia's President
Vaclav Havel said: "I believe the freedom today enjoyed by
our mass media does not at all mean that RFE has lost its
meaning." He added, "There are numberless spheres where it
can continue to serve our nations well at this time -- better
than our own mass media."
   It is likely that in five or 10 years Radio Free Europe
will have outlived its usefulness in countries such as
Czechoslovakia. At that point, Steve Forbes, head of the
Board for International Broadcasting, suggests that certain
RFE services be privatized and sold to local interests. Until
then, continued funding of Radio Free Europe's mission is one
of the best ways the U.S. can help ensure a prosperous and
stable Europe.
   This fall a bipartisan commission will evaluate the work
of both Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty and the VOA, and make
recommendations to Congress on their future. Despite budget
pressures, the $360 million annual investment in U.S.-funded
radio networks should be maintained. The dividends from their
work will continue to pour in for years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900813-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900813-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dutch Trade Balance Fell in May
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   THE HAGUE -- The Dutch balance of trade slid into a
deficit of 900 million guilders (US$500 million) in May but
registered a surplus of 2.2 billion guilders for the first
five months of this year, the Netherlands Economics Ministry
said.
   The May deficit resulted from a strong 9% rise in the
value of imports at a time when exports were falling 2%.
Imports in May were valued at 20.6 billion guilders compared
with 19.6 billion guilders of exports.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900813-0099
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900813-0099.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Cracking the Drug Problem
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   The watchdogs of progress and enlightenment have been
quite busy of late, snarling at the war on drugs, and
sneering at its adherents. Take, for example, the recent
Herblock howler -- a cartoon showing drug chief William J.
Bennett in full martial regalia, about to lead troops in an
armed assault on the patients of a drug-rehabilitation
center.
   Among the other anti-drug war warriors, count the
advocates of "personal freedom," who would rather blame the
drug problem on everything from alienation to consumerism
rather than acknowledge how much permissiveness has to do
with the growth of this tragedy. Then there are the
progressives, who maintain that enforcement measures and a
war on drugs can't work. The only solution to drugs, they
argue, is to attack poverty and racism, itself a racist
notion suggesting that the minority poor have no will of
their own. An all-fronts war of condemnation, law enforcement
and neighborhood activism seems to have upset the agendas of
the enlightened. What was particularly upsetting about this
war to advanced thinkers was its emphasis of an old value
known as moral leadership.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yet drug czar Bennett soldiered on and behold, there are
now signs that the war may be having its effect. The major
reporting systems all indicate a drop in drug use for the
first time since the mid-1980s, when the drug epidemic began
spiraling out of control. Cocaine emergencies dropped off
sharply in 1989, according to data collected by the Drug
Abuse Warning Network (DAWN), the agency that monitors
hospital emergency rooms in major cities. Heroin emergencies
also fell, though to a lesser degree. While no single
indicator tells the whole story, the DAWN report is
significant because its data comes from centers of hard-core
drug use.
   Perhaps more significantly, drugs have lost their old
luster among the young. According to the 1989 High School
Senior Survey, the already high rate of disapproval of drugs
continues to climb among high-school seniors. The
overwhelming majority of the students surveyed disapproved
not just of cocaine, moreover, but also of occasional
marijuana use. That response would surely have been
inconceivable a little over a decade ago.
   The National Household Survey on Drug Abuse provided a
similar omen in its report of a 37% drop in drug use since
1985. What is particularly telling is that this survey
reports largely on middle-class drug consumption. The drug
epidemic can be said to have arrived, truly, when parents and
teachers, businessmen and bus drivers and other average
citizens embraced the notion of "recreational drugs." In
short order they became the dealers' best customers. If
middle-class Americans no longer buy the notion that drugs
are acceptable, we have turned a major corner in the war.
   On the supply side, too, there are hopeful signs. Cocaine
prices have skyrocketed, while the purity level of the
available cocaine has dropped dramatically. Both are sure
signs of a disruption in supply. In Bolivia, coca farming has
become unprofitable, the direct result of harsh measures
lately taken both in Bolivia and elsewhere.
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco deserves considerable
credit for his efforts. After the murder of a Colombian
presidential candidate, President Barco embarked on a program
of total war against traffickers, including massive arrests
and extraditions.
   None of this is to say, of course, that the drug lords
have been destroyed. It is to say a hard line on law
enforcement can and clearly does work.
   Charleston, South Carolina, saw that rule proved when
Police Chief Reuben Greenberg simply used round-the-clock
surveillance to force dealers from turf to turf, thus cutting
them off from their customers. When his men move in on an
operation, the chief told columnist William Raspberry, they
seize the furniture, the air conditioner, the phones, the
very chair the dealer sits on, so that he can't do business
the next day. Chief Greenberg's hard-line tactics have had a
dramatic effect on Charleston's crime rate, now lower by 45%.
   In the crime-plagued cities, the fervor against drugs and
dealers mounts. None of this, again, is to say that victory
is at hand. It is to note real progress in the war on drugs.
A most important sign of that progress is the perception, in
inner cities as elsewhere, that drug users are losers.
   When rock stars and other beautiful people began to flaunt
and glamorize drugs, they were also sending the catastrophic
signal that drugs were associated with power and status. The
deglamorization of drugs now in evidence among all classes of
our society is the best indication to date that the war
against drugs is winnable. In arguing these many years that
such a war could not be won, the naysayers failed to reckon
with the power of moral leadership, its insistence on
accountability, its distinction between right and wrong. If
we are seeing some rays of hope in the battle against drugs,
it is mainly thanks to the fact that that weapon has at last
been put to work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
