<HL>
   Price Stern Sloan Inc.
   And Mattel Sign Pact
   For Barbie Doll Books
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3A
</SO>
<CO>
   MAT DIS
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Mattel Inc. said it signed an exclusive
licensing agreement with Price Stern Sloan Inc. to produce a
series of books, including a cookbook, based on its Barbie
doll toy.
   The books will add to a plethora of products Mattel is
introducing around the image of Barbie, the world's
best-selling plastic playmate. Already, the toy maker has
unvieled several new Barbie Style products, including a line
of girl-sized costumes, bed sheets and accessories.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Over time, Mattel has said it plans to take Barbie beyond
the toy category and into children's clothing, beauty
products and other consumer goods -- hoping that by doing so,
the company will bolster sales of the doll.
   Mattel said it is considering several proposals from movie
producers to take Barbie to the silver screen. A Mattel
spokesman said a decision on whether to make a movie hasn't
been made. One consideration the company has always had is
that a Barbie movie, which would show how the doll supposedly
sounds and acts, would impinge on each individual girl's
fantasies about the doll, the Mattel spokesman said.
   Barbie accounted for $600 million of Mattel's $1.2 billion
in total revenue for 1989.
   Los Angeles-based Price Stern Sloan, a publisher and
distributor of children's books, said it plans to introduce
the first of several lines of Barbie books in the spring of
1991.
   In addition, Price Stern said that in July, it entered
into a licensing agreement with Walt Disney Co. to produce an
electronic wand with a Mickey Mouse head and to publish six
books featuring Disney characters.
</TEXT>
