<HL>
   Ford to Put Cash
   Into Toronto Auto
   Parts Supplier
   ----
   By Larry M. Greenberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   TMG.A F MAGAF
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Ford Motor Co. said it has agreed to inject
cash into Magna International Inc., one of Ford's major
outside suppliers of auto parts, in order to ensure a
continued supply of plastic bumpers from the financially
strapped company.
   Neither company would reveal the size of Ford's
investment, but Toronto-based Magna said the deal represents
a "major step" in its program to restructure 1.09 billion
Canadian dollars (US$949.5 million) in debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Magna spokesman Brian Colburn called the agreement with
Ford a "vote of confidence" in Magna's ability to continue
operating. Magna, which has been plagued by overcapacity and
a slowdown in the auto industry, supplies parts to all of the
Big Three U.S. auto makers.
   Under terms of the agreement, a Ford subsidiary will
acquire 49% and Magna will own 51% of a new company, Conix
Canada Inc., that has been set up to acquire various assets
from Magna's Decoma International Inc. unit. The assets
include a new 530,000 square-foot plastic bumper
manufacturing plant in Guelph, Ontario. The plant, which will
employ about 500 people after production gets under way early
next year, will eventually replace a smaller facility
currently in use in Toronto, Mr. Colburn said.
   The joint venture company also will acquire Magna's
mould-making plant in Concord, Ontario, which has 130
employees.
   In addition, Magna said Ford has agreed to purchase the
property of Magna's interior component manufacturing plant in
Nashville, Ill., and to lease the facility back to Magna.
Ford also will provide a loan to a Magna subsidiary in the
U.S.
   The pact with Ford is Magna's second significant move to
reduce its debt load since the company announced in March it
was in technical default on some of its bank loans. Last
month, Magna said it agreed to sell its automotive electric
motors division to a unit of Siemens AG of West Germany.
Analysts estimated that deal was worth about C$70 million.
   Mr. Colburn said Magna is negotiating with its creditors
to secure a standstill agreement on the company's loans. He
said Magna aims to cut its debt load by about half over the
next 12 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900813-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900813-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   Dollar Loses Appeal as Haven in a Crisis
   Because of U.S. Economic Fundamentals
   ----
   By Alison Woods and Candace Cumberbatch
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST JAPAN CANDA EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- What little safe-harbor appeal the wobbly
dollar had is wearing off, currency analysts say.
   While the Iraq-Kuwait crisis might, in other
circumstances, have prompted an enthusiastic rush to buy
dollars, U.S. economic fundamentals now are simply viewed as
too bearish for the dollar to qualify as a "safe" investment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's a surprise that the dollar is not higher," given the
events in the Middle East, says Victor Polce, manager of
corporate trading at Algemene Bank Nederland in New York.
   The dollar's movement Friday surprised many market
participants, as it stumbled against most other major
currencies even after statements by Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein sent shock waves through U.S. financial markets.
   When the dollar sagged, gold quickly replaced it as the
investment of choice. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold for current delivery settled at $396.90, up $11.10 an
ounce. Estimated volume was a heavy seven million ounces.
   In late currency trading here Friday, the dollar was
changing hands at 1.5905 marks and 150.45 yen, compared with
1.5965 marks and 149.80 yen late Thursday. Compared with a
week earlier, the dollar was about unchanged, while gold was
up nearly $20 an ounce.
   In early trading in Tokyo Monday, the dollar was quoted at
150.15 yen, up from 149.75 at the close there Friday. The
dollar was also trading at 1.5823 marks.
   "The dollar is going to be heading south," probably to
1.50-1.55 marks and the "low 140s" against the yen, as soon
as the last of its "safe haven" appeal is worn off, Mr. Polce
of Algemene Bank says.
   While the yen is currently being held back by worries that
higher oil prices will aggravate Japan's already substantial
inflation pressures, the recent rise in Japanese money market
rates should help the yen strengthen eventually, according to
Mr. Polce.
   The market's hands-off mood about the dollar stems from a
series of ills that have pushed the U.S. economy to the brink
of recession. Those problems include a troubled banking
industry, a sluggish manufacturing sector and growing
unemployment.
   "There's a good fundamental camp that has wanted to see
the dollar go lower" because of the economy, says Rick
Porter, manager of corporate trading at Westpac Banking Corp.
   Among the U.S. economy's several problems, the most
worrisome at the moment is the surge in oil prices caused by
Iraq's takeover of Kuwait. The September crude oil futures
contract has risen more than $6 a barrel in the past two
weeks to settle Friday at $26.23.
   The higher oil prices couldn't have hit the U.S. at a
worse time: Inflation is already a stubborn problem burdening
the economy, and with the oil-price surge the Federal Reserve
can't ease credit aggressively to stimulate growth.
   At the current rate of economic activity, some analysts
see negative growth as possible for the U.S.'s third and
fourth quarters after a feeble 1.2% annual rate of expansion
in the second quarter and 1.7% in the first quarter.
   Roger Brinner, chief economist at DRI-McGraw Hill in
Lexington, Mass., says U.S. economic growth could be cut by
0.7 percentage point in 1991 if oil stays near its current
price for a lengthy period.
   Mr. Brinner sees better prospects for Europe and Japan,
saying that inflation-adjusted growth in European Community
countries might be curbed by only half a point next year if
oil prices stay up and that growth in Japan may be trimmed by
0.6 percentage point.
   The generally stronger economies of Western Europe and
Japan should help those nations withstand any oil price shock
better than the U.S., Mr. Brinner says.
   In early trading in Hong Kong Monday, gold was quoted at
$394.25 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
